<F P=100> Latin America &amp; Caribbean </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Meets Chilean Secretary General </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302081194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1052 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0302081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Zhang Rongdian (1728 2837 0368)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 2 Feb (XINHUA) -- While meeting with 
Secretary General Enrique Correa Rios of the Chilean Government 
this afternoon at Diaoyutai State Guest House, Qian Qichen, 
State Council vice premier and foreign minister, expressed the 
belief that the traditional friendly relationship between China 
and Chile will continue to develop constantly. He also hoped 
that the two countries would carry out more extensive 
cooperation in the area of international affairs. 
  Qian Qichen appreciated the Chilean Government's resolute 
pursuit of the "one China" and nonintervention in other 
countries' internal affairs policies. He recalled President 
Yang Shangkun's successful visit to Chile in 1990 and Chilean 
President Aylwin's successful visit to China in 1992. He said 
the two countries have made big strides in economic development. 
He said these have provided excellent prospects for both sides 
to further carry out mutually beneficial cooperation in diverse 
forms and through various channels. 
  On behalf of the Chilean Government, Correa congratulated 
China for its diplomatic achievements in recent years. He said 
China has played an important role in promoting peace and 
development in Asia and in the world. China has consistently 
stood for adopting peaceful means to settle international 
disputes. Internationally, reform and opening up have won honor 
and prestige for China. 
  Correa added that the Chilean Government would strive to 
further strengthen ties with China in various fields. 
  Qian Qichen and Correa also exchanged views on the 
international situation. 
  Correa arrived in Beijing for a goodwill visit on the 
evening 
of 31 January at the Chinese Government's invitation. 
  Tomorrow, Correa and his party will leave Beijing and visit 
Shanghai and Shenzhen. 

</TEXT>

