<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   British Officials Present PRC With Airport Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0302052694 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 3 
Feb 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> HK0302052694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporters] </F>
  [Text] The British side of the Joint Liaison Group's 
airport committee yesterday presented China with the Hong Kong 
Government's latest Chek Lap Kok funding proposal. British 
officials are hoping a meeting can be held and an agreement 
reached before the end of the month. They also hope the issue 
will not be complicated by the Government's tabling of the 
remaining part of the 1994/95 electoral bill in the Legislative 
Council. 
  The Chinese State Council's Hong Kong and Macao Affairs 
Office was also given an outline of the proposal by the British 
Ambassador to China, Sir Robin McLaren. "The new offer is a 
very good one and ought to be acceptable to the Chinese side," 
Mr McLaren said. 
  Zhang Junsheng, a vice director of the Hong Kong branch of 
Xinhua (the New China News Agency), said the Chinese side needed 
to study the new offer before making any comment. But Mr Zhang 
criticised Governor Chris Patten for saying the new financing 
package was an excellent Lunar New Year present. "This is not a 
present he gives us. It belongs to Hong Kong. All (we) hope is 
just that he will not misspend the money," Mr Zhang said. Mr 
Patten yesterday pledged that the Government would not reduce 
spending on public projects in order to pay for the airport. 
  Meanwhile, the Liberals' airport spokesman, Steven Poon 
Kwok-lim, said yesterday the party would support the latest 
airport financing proposal. Mr Poon said, under the proposal, 
the debt-equity ratio would be even lower than their suggested 
1:1, much lower than other projects. It is understood that the 
Executive Council on Tuesday endorsed the fourth financing 
proposal, which will see the Government's injection to the 
airport project increase by $15 billion to $60 billion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

