<H3> <TI>   Article Notes Senior Statesmen's Remarks on Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0202083694 Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO in Chinese 2 Feb 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> HK0202083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Special article" by staff reporter: "Yang Shangkun's and </F>
Tian Jiyun's Remarks on Reform Are Worth Pondering"] 
  [Text] Recently, senior statesman Yang Shangkun and Tian 
Jiyun, vice chairman of the National People's Congress, 
separately visited Guangdong. Their statements, which differ 
from normal ones, are worth pondering. 
  A Guangdong official disclosed that Yang Shangkun met with 
provincial officials while in Guangdong. He listened to an 
account given by these officials. Yang, who has kept a 
relatively low profile since the 14th CPC Congress, talked 
volubly. He expressed support for Guangdong's reform, saying 
that the province had a correct guiding ideology, which was 
worth recommending. He particularly asked the special economic 
regions to consolidate their achievements. 
  It is said that Yang Shangkun spoke highly of Guangdong's 
proposal in the new round of reform of reestablishing the 
province's superiority, particularly the superiority of Shenzhen 
and Zhuhai, which included the tentative ideas of establishing 
the Nanhua financial center and setting up a free trade zone. 
When the question of Shanghai's Pudong was mentioned, however, 
Yang Shangkun remained silent. 
  During his visit to Shenzhen the other day, Tian Jiyun 
stressed "reform, opening up, delegation of powers, and 
flexibility," saying that herein lies the crux of mainland's 
economic development. 
  Tian Jiyun spoke highly of the recent reforms. He said that 
a market economic mechanism will be gradually introduced to 
replace the forsaken planned economic model, which was 
disadvantageous to development of productive forces. 
  Guangdong officials say that the remarks of Yang Shangkun 
and 
Tian Jiyun meant more than what they say and are worth 
pondering. It shows that there are differences within the CPC on 
a number of issues. 
  Reportedly, there are also serious differences within the 
State Council. Besides external affairs and the Three Gorges 
project, Premier Li Peng will not bother about other businesses. 
Zhu Rongji and Zou Jiahua argued contentiously as they shared 
different views on the capital for key construction projects. 
Qian Qichen and Li Lanqing also attended to their own business. 

</TEXT>

