<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Foreign Minister's Visit to Boston </TI></H3>
<H4>   Explains Foreign Policy </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302083994 Taipei CNA in English 0724 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By David Wang and Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Boston, Feb. 2 (CNA) -- The people of the Republic 
of China [ROC] on Taiwan believe that they should and must 
assume a more active role in the international community to help 
enhance regional stability and security, ROC Minister of Foreign 
Affairs Chien Fu said Wednesday [2 February]. 
  Chien made the remarks during a one-hour speech to students 
and faculty of the Harvard Business School. He spoke on 
Taiwan's role in Asia-Pacific economic growth. 
  He noted that the Asia-Pacific, which boasts the highest 
economic growth rate in the world, would benefit from the ROC's 
participation in regional development and security programs. 
  He also said that closer regional economic, commercial and 
technological cooperation is key to avoiding political and 
military confrontation. 
  He stressed that as a member of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum, Taiwan registers firmly its right to 
participate in APEC meetings and activities on an equal basis 
with other members. 
  "We intend to share our valuable developmental experience 
with others by hosting more APEC activities in the future," 
Chien explained. 
  But Chien also said that Taiwan cannot tolerate the 
introduction of political or sovereignty issues in the informal 
consultative forum. 
  Chien said that the ROC is now devoting new emphasis to 
establishing Taiwan as an Asia-Pacific regional operations 
center, where people, capital, goods, and information can move 
in and out freely. 
  In a question and answer session after the speech, Chien 
reaffirmed that the ROC is a sovereign nation. He predicted 
that when per-capita income in Mainland China reaches between 
US$1,000 and US$2,000 by the year 2000, their people will yearn 
for freedom, democracy and human rights. 
  After the speech, Chien and his wife called on the Governor 
of Massachusetts William Weld. They exchanged gifts during a 
cordial half-hour chat. 
  Chien also had lunch with professors of the Harvard Business 
School at noon. 
  Chien will return to Taipei Friday after winding up his 
weeklong visit in the U.S. during which he also made a speech at 
Boston University. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26116 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi023_v_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Foreign Minister's Visit to Boston </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Resuming Burkina Faso Ties </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302083894 Taipei CNA in English 0717 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By David Wang And Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Boston, Feb. 2 (CNA) -- The Republic of China [ROC] 
will send agricultural experts to Burkina Faso to help the west 
African country develop its agriculture and economy, Foreign 
Affairs Minister Chien Fu said Wednesday [2 February]. 
  Chien, who is currently on a speaking tour here, made the 
statement shortly after the ROC and Burkina Faso issued a joint 
communique in Taipei on the resumption of full diplomatic 
relations. 
  The ROC first established diplomatic ties with Burkina Faso, 
then known as Upper Volta, in 1961, but suspended such ties in 
1973 after the African nation recognized Beijing. 
  Chien said the ROC stationed an agricultural mission in 
Burkina Faso in the 1960. "Many Burkina Faso people still 
remembered the achievements of our agricultural mission in 
helping raise their rice production," he noted. 
  The ROC and Burkina Faso began discussion of resuming 
diplomatic ties two years ago. The Burkina Faso cabinet 
formally agreed to resume ties with the ROC in January, Chien 
said. 
  With an area of 274,000 square kilometers and a population 
of 
9.5 million, Burkina Faso became an independent nation in 1960 
after decades of French colonial rule. It is rich in mineral 
resources and produces large quantities of cotton and livestock. 
Its political situation is stable, Chien said. 
  Moreover, Chien added, Burkina Faso has great influence on 
other west African nations. "The resumption of diplomatic ties 
with Burkina Faso will facilitate our effort to promote 
exchanges with that part of the world," he noted. 
  The ROC now maintains full diplomatic ties with eight 
African 
nations -- South Africa, Swaziland, Malawi, Liberia, Niger, 
Guinea-Bissau, the Central African Republic and Burkina Faso. 
  It has opened a consulate general in Calabar, Nigeria and 
set 
up representative offices in Madagascar, Zaire and Angola 
bearing the ROC's full national title. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

