<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Attend GATT Meeting in Morocco </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302083694 Taipei CNA in English 0650 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y. C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 3 (CNA) -- Preparations are under way 
for Taiwan to attend a ministerial-level meeting of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) in Morocco April 15, an 
economics official reported Thursday [3 February]. 
  Tsai Lien-sheng, a section chief of the Board of Foreign 
Trade under the Ministry of Economic Affairs, said that Taiwan 
has been invited to attend the meeting, in which the 112 GATT 
contracting parties will sign the agreement reached during the 
Uruguay Round talks in mid-December. 
  The GATT meeting will also make a final decision on the 
exact 
time for the establishment of the World Trade Organization 
(WTO), Tsai pointed out. 
  Under the Uruguay Round accord, all GATT signatories are set 
to become members of the WTO, which will be given tougher 
enforcement powers to supersede GATT. 
  GATT members have attached great importance to the Morocco 
meeting, Tsai said, noting the European Union and the United 
States will reportedly send 200-member delegations. 
  Economic Affairs Minister P.K. Chiang is expected to lead 
the 
Taiwan delegation to the meeting, Tsai said. 
  Taiwan, accepted as an observer of the Geneva-based world 
trade regulating body in September 1992, hopes to become a full 
member by the end of this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

