<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Shops Introduce Installment Payment Plans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302131294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1248 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Several stores in 
Shanghai, China's largest metropolis, have adopted installment 
payment plans, a breakthrough in the city's commercial industry. 
  So far, some 100 citizens have made purchases under the new 
credit system, buying color televisions, air conditioners and 
refrigerators. After paying one-sixth of a product's purchase 
price, customers should pay off the balance owed within a year. 
  The service is staged by Shanghai Yintong Trust Ltd., 
jointly 
funded by the Shanghai Investment and Trust Corporation and 
other local and Hong Kong partners. 
  It is stipulated that customers with monthly incomes above 
600 yuan can apply for the installment plan. They may begin to 
buy goods on credit after passing a Yintong Ltd. capital and 
credit assessment. 
  Shanghai First department store, which experimented with 
installment sales last November, has offered consultancy to more 
than 2,000 interested customers. 
  Many consumers think that the plan can help them make 
reasonable family economic arrangements and relieve their 
worries over price hikes. 
  This month, three other shops in the city have also adopted 
the measure. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

