<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Now `Largest' Gold Ornament Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302082594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0659 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai has become 
China's largest gold ornament market, according to "CHINA 
BUSINESS NEWS". 
  A survey shows that sales of such ornaments in the city last 
year were 20 tons, an increase of five tons over the previous 
year and double the 1991 figure. 
  Shanghai people's average possession of gold ornaments rose 
from 0.77 grams per capita in 1991 to 1.54 grams last year. 
  Trading in gold ornaments resumed in China in 1982. 
  The newspaper attributed the fast growth to the rise of 
Shanghai residents' income, the custom of purchasing gold 
ornaments, and the change of habits from keeping gold for its 
value to acquiring it both for its value and its decoration. 
  With approval of the People's Bank, Shanghai set up 300 gold 
retail shops toward the end of last year and some 150 shops are 
waiting for official approval. 
  There were only 40 such shops in the city a decade ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26130 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi023_p_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangdong Officials Use Gallup Polls in Governing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302113594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1058 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, February 3 (XINHUA) -- The methodology 
invented by the late American professor George Gallup to 
discover what's on the minds of the public is now helping local 
government officials to govern better. 
  Public attitudes ranging from commodity prices and the image 
of public servants to environmental pollution and housing reform 
are what a small research agency in south China's boomtown of 
Guangzhou has been finding out since 1990. 
  Once or twice every month, local media devote time and space 
to publish the findings on matters of social focus. 
  The feedback prompts the municipal government to adopt 
measures to solve the problems that affect the life of local 
residents. 
  Last year a survey found that 70 percent of Guangzhou people 
are dissatisfied with the jammed traffic conditions. The 
relevant departments took immediate action to ban bicycle 
traffic on 11 major roads. 
  A follow-up telephone survey, however, revealed that 55 
percent of the people were against the new policy. Then the 
city solicited ideas from the public and came up with a plan 
that worked. 
  Xu Yucong, an employee at the Guangzhou public opinion 
research center, which conducted these surveys, said that the 
center aims to reflect the concerns of people and serves to jog 
the minds of policy makers. "In this way, we can draw more 
attention from the leaders whose policies can help harmonize the 
multi-faceted relationships in society." 
  To date, the center has conducted over 60 surveys, involving 
more than 1.4 million residents. 
  Xu said some of the findings touched on sensitive issues. 
But the municipal government backed their endeavors and 
considered the practice a main channel of communication of the 
Communist Party and government organizations with the general 
public. 
  Xu said the center is able to keep itself objective and 
unbiased by maintaining total financial independence. 
  Although the Gallup methods have not spread to other parts 
of 
the country in finding out public opinion, major cities such as 
Shanghai, Tianjin and the capital Beijing do have "mayor's hot 
lines" that citizens can dial at any time to voice their 
grievances and proposals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

