<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen To Speed `Internationalization' of Banks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302140694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1342 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Shenzhen, one of 
the earliest special economic zones in south China's Guangdong 
Province, will take measures to speed up the 
internationalization of its banking industry, according to a 
municipal banking working conference held here today. 
  The measures include: 
  -- More overseas financial organizations will be allowed to 
set up branches in Shenzhen and foreign investment in such 
sectors as banks, trust, foundations, securities and insurance 
companies will be encouraged. 
  -- The business scope of foreign-funded financial 
organizations will be admitted into such areas as savings, loans 
and accounting in RMB [renminbi], the Chinese currency. 
  -- Locally-funded financial organizations are encouraged to 
set up branches overseas and transnational banks. 
  At present, there are 41 foreign-funded financial 
organizations in Shenzhen, including banks, securities companies 
and insurance companies. Over the past decade or so, they have 
introduced more than one billion U.S. dollars of foreign funds 
into Shenzhen. 
  Shenzhen plans to increase its savings by 18 billion yuan 
this year, an increase of 36 percent over last year, according 
to today's conference. 
  In 1993, the banking industry of Shenzhen maintained healthy 
momentum. At the end of last year, it reported a savings 
balance of 65.7 billion yuan, an increase of 10.2 billion yuan 
over the beginning of 1993, up 18.4 percent; a loan balance of 
50.2 billion yuan, an increase of 12.6 billion yuan and up 33.6 
percent; and a foreign currency loan balance of 3.66 billion 
U.S. dollars, an increase of 800 million U.S. dollars and up 
16.1 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

