<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xinjiang Secretary Meets With Local Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302120994 Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network in Mandarin 
1330 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0302120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Xinjiang News" program] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday, the autonomous regional party committee 
and people's government held a discussion meeting, attended by 
principal leaders of prefectures, autonomous prefectures, and 
cities. At the meeting, principal leaders of prefectures, 
autonomous prefectures, and cities exchanged their views on the 
progress of last year's work, the experience they gained and 
what they learned therefrom, as well as their plans for the new 
year and their hopes and proposals for the autonomous region's 
policy on macroeconomic regulations and control. 
  After hearing reports by leaders of various prefectures, 
autonomous prefectures, and cities, regional party Secretary 
Song Hanliang pointed out: Whether or not the reform, opening 
up, and economic development carried out by Xinjiang can be 
accelerated depends on the actual progress made by various 
prefectures, autonomous prefectures, and cities; and also 
depends on how the frontline leaders command and organize their 
men to implement the policies. 
  He said: Our regional and border trade reflects that a 
market mechanism is gradually taking shape in Xinjiang. Guided 
by the principle of emancipating the minds, the government 
formulated a series of essential policies, which played an 
important role in providing services and improving 
infrastructural facilities in various ports. If the same thing 
is done in our industrial and agricultural sectors as well as to 
our infrastructure, we can achieve development with great speed 
and high-efficiency. 
  Leading comrades of Xinjiang Autonomous Region, including 
Abulaidi Amudurexiti, Zhang Fusen, Wang Lequan, Keyum Bawudun, 
Zhou Shengtao, and Hailiqiemu Silamu, also attended the meeting. 

</TEXT>

