<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xinjiang Economic Meeting Outlines Guidelines </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202145094 Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network in Mandarin 
1330 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0202145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video from the "Xinjiang News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] An autonomous regional conference on economic work 
and trade was held in Urumqi yesterday. Autonomous regional 
leaders Abulaiti Amudurexiti, Wang Lequan, and Keyum Bawundun 
attended the conference. 
  In 1993, our region reaped bumper harvests in agriculture, 
registered industrial growth, enjoyed booming market activity, 
conducted brisk border trade, increased financial revenue, 
improved living standards, and achieved initial success in 
implementing central macroeconomic regulatory and control 
measures. By and large, Xinjiang enjoyed good financial order 
and economic operations. Nevertheless, secondary and tertiary 
industries, which are primarily based on village and town 
enterprises, still constituted a small proportion of the 
economy. Although industrial production developed well, the 
general level of economic efficiency in enterprises remained 
low. 
  The general guiding thought for our region's economic work 
and trade in 1994 is: Earnestly implementing the guidelines of 
the Third Plenary Session of the 14th CPC Central Committee and 
the Sixth Enlarged Plenary Session of the Fourth Xinjiang 
Autonomous Regional Party Committee, turning reform into a 
driving force, focusing on development, exploiting resources, 
optimizing the economic structure, opening wider to the outside 
world, improving economic efficiency, and promoting rapid 
development of Xinjiang's economy based on high efficiency. This 
year, we should expedite the pace of deepening reform in 
state-run enterprises, further improve large and medium 
enterprises, vigorously advance tehnological progress in 
enterprises, and further improve quality control. We should 
also accelerate the development of village and town enterprises, 
nurture new economic growth sectors, accelerate economic and 
market development, increase commercial and trade flows, tighten 
and improve macroeconomic regulation and control, and coordinate 
work in all aspects of economic operations. 

</TEXT>

