<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xinjiang Planning Conference Views 1993, 1994 Work </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202145394 Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network in Mandarin 
1330 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0202145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Urumqi Xinjiang Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video from the "Xinjiang News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] An autonomous regional conference on planning and 
prices was held in Urumqi recently. Autonomous regional leaders 
Abulaiti Amudurexiti, Wang Lequan, and Keyum Bawundun attended 
the conference. 
  In carrying out planning and pricing work in 1993, Xinjiang 
unremittingly carried out the central task of economic 
construction and endeavored to solve salient problems that had 
surfaced during the course of economic operations, in accordance 
with the arrangements made by the autonomous regional party 
committee's work conference. This helped promote economic 
development. The gross regional product in 1993 is expected to 
total 37.7 billion yuan, an increase of approximately 10 percent 
over the preceding year. 
  In carrying out planning and pricing work in 1994, Xinjiang 
should strengthen the status of agriculture as the foundation of 
the national economy, and stabilize the household contract 
responsibility system with remuneration linked to output, as 
well as the dual management system that combines household with 
collective operations. It should make efforts to restructure 
the rural economy and crop farming, and steadfastly engage in 
the construction of infrastructure, basic industries, and 
industries producing major raw and semifinished materials, in 
order to ease "bottlenecks" and create fine conditions for 
developing the economy and opening up to the outside world. In 
1994, we should place greater emphasis on assessing and making 
flexible use of our reserves and assets, and intensify 
technological transformation, while maintaining moderate growth 
in capital construction investment. To meet the demands of 
exploration and development at the three major oil fields in 
Xinjiang, we should closely integrate technical transformation 
with capital construction, develop a number of related 
industries that serve the needs of oil fields, and promote oil 
field development. We should ensure that oil fields and the 
local economy spur each other on for the sake of common 
development. 
  While continuing to accelerate economic development in the 
comprehensive economic development belt north of Tian Shan, we 
should also place great emphasis on economic development in 
southern Xinjiang. We should increase capital construction 
investment, expedite poverty relief work, and gradually narrow 
the gap between southern and northern Xinjiang. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

