<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Calls U.S. Report `Irresponsible' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302085994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0844 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- The United States 
has no right to make irresponsible remarks about the internal 
affairs of China, or of any other country, Chinese Foreign 
Ministry Spokesman Wu Jianmin said here today. 
  Asked to comment, at the ministry's weekly news conference, 
on the human rights report issued by the U.S. State Department 
which criticized the human rights situation in China, Wu said: 
"It is utterly unreasonable and totally irresponsible for the 
so-called human rights report to distort, criticize and attack 
the domestic situation in China." 
  The U.S. State Department released the report on February 1. 
  "The issue of human rights falls in essence within the 
sovereignty of each country, which is embodied in its domestic 
legislations," Wu said. 
  "China's constitution and relevant laws have fully 
guaranteed 
the Chinese people of all nationalities of every democratic 
right," said the spokesman, adding that the report had turned a 
blind eye to this fact. 
  "We are resolutely opposed to interference in our internal 
affairs under the excuse of human rights," Wu said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

