<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   AFP on Human Rights Report </H4>
<F P=102> HK0302081094 Hong Kong AFP in English 0730 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK0302081094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, Feb 3 (AFP)--China slammed Thursday a U.S. 
State Department report that criticised Beijing's human rights 
record, labelling it "utterly unreasonable" and a gross 
distortion of the facts. 
  China's constitution guarantees its citizens every 
democratic 
right and it is "utterly unreasonable and totally irresponsible 
for the so-called human rights report ... to turn a blind eye to 
that fact," Foreign Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin told a weekly 
press briefing. 
  The U.S. report, published February 1, said that while China 
had made limited progress on human rights last year, it had 
still engaged in extrajudicial killings, torture and other 
abuses. 
  The report aimed to "distort, criticise and attack the 
domestic situation in China," Wu said, adding that the United 
States has no right "to make irresponsible remarks" about the 
internal affairs of China or any other country. 
  The publication of the U.S. report came as China and the 
United States are continuing negtiations on renewal of China's 
most-favoured-nation (MFN) trading status, which Washington has 
made conditional on significant progress in human rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

