<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   More on Human Rights Issue </H4>
<F P=102> HK0302084294 Hong Kong AFP in English 0829 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK0302084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Beijing, Feb 3 (AFP)--China slammed Thursday a 
US State Department report that criticised Beijing's human 
rights record, labelling it "utterly unreasonable" and a gross 
distortion of the facts. [passage omitted] 
  The publication of the report and China's aggressive 
response 
is sure to further hamper Sino-U.S. negotiations over 
Washington's renewal of China's most-favoured-nation (MFN) 
trading status, which President Bill Clinton has tied to 
significant progress in human rights. 
  [Foreign Ministry spokesman] Wu also accused Washington of 
using the human rights issue to undermine China's sovereign 
rights, reiterating that Beijing is "resolutely opposed to 
interference in our internal affairs under the excuse of human 
rights." In a clear reference to the detention of political 
prisoners, Wu stressed that the functioning of China's judiciary 
"is something that the Chinese government cannot interfere in, 
let alone any foreign forces." 
  "It is not appropriate to mix human rights issues and legal 
issues," he added. 
  The U.S. report said China had released some prominent 
political dissidents, but continued to hold hundreds and perhaps 
thousands more, and often engaged in torture in prisons, 
especially in sensitive regions such as Tibet. "Fundamental 
human rights provided for in the Chinese Constitution frequently 
are ignored in practice, and challenges to the Communist Party's 
political authority are often dealt with harshly and 
arbitrarily," the report said. [passage omitted] 
  Asked if China was willing to make gestures in the human 
rights area in order to make it easier for Clinton to recommend 
MFN renewal, Wu simply reiterated the government's position of 
holding dialogue with other countries "on the basis of equality 
and mutual respect." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

