<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Airport Issue </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302103494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1014 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Maintaining 
Sino-British cooperation on the Hong Kong issue is in the 
interest of both China and Britain, a Chinese spokesman said 
here today. 
  Wu Jianmin, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said this at a 
routine news conference this afternoon, when asked to comment on 
former British Ambassador to China Sir Percy Cradock's criticism 
of Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten in an article carried by the 
"SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST". 
  Wu said that China has noticed that there are different 
voices within Britain over the Hong Kong issue. 
  He noted that to maintain cooperation between China and 
Britain on the matter of Hong Kong is in accordance with the 
interests of the two sides. 
  He said that Patten's intransigence and uncooperative 
attitude would end up harming Britain's own interests. 
  Cradock was ambassador to China from June 1978 to December 
1983. 
  On China's reaction toward the recently tabled fourth 
funding 
plan for the construction of the new Hong Kong airport, Wu said 
that the Chinese Government had just received the new financial 
arrangement plan from the British side and was studying it 
earnestly. 
  He said that the new airport issue should be settled in 
accordance with the memorandum of understanding reached between 
China and Britain. 
  In the process of such settlement, the British side should 
demonstrate its sincerity, Wu said, adding that the Chinese side 
has already demonstrated a lot of sincerity over the Hong Kong 
matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

