<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Lifts Trade Embargo Against Vietnam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402100194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0836 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0402100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Xu Changyin (1776 7022 6892)] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 3 Feb [XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Clinton today announced at the White House that the United 
States has decided to lift its 19-year-old trade embargo against 
Vietnam. 
  Clinton said: Over the past year, with Vietnam's 
cooperation, the United States has made "major and substantial 
progress" [zhong da de shi zhi xing jin zhan 6850 1129 4104 1395 
6347 1840 6651 1455] in finding American MIAs from the Vietnam 
war. Therefore, the best way to ensure Vietnam's continued 
cooperation is to "end the trade embargo" against Vietnam. He 
said the United States will continue to work to find out the 
whereabouts of those American servicemen who are still missing. 
  Before Clinton made the announcement, he discussed the 
matter 
with family members of some American MIAs. Some American 
Vietnam war veterans organizations and family members of MIAs 
had asked President Clinton not to lift the trade embargo before 
the whereabouts of all American MIAs are known. 
  Clinton also announced that he has decided to establish a 
liaison office in Vietnam to "provide services for Americans" in 
Vietnam and to "help us to pursue a human rights dialogue with 
the Vietnamese Government." But, he expressly pointed out that 
"these actions do not constitute a normalization of our 
relationships." Before our relations can be normalized, "we 
must have more progress, more cooperation, and more answers." 
To achieve this goal, Clinton said he will "send another 
high-level U.S. delegation to Vietnam" "this spring." 
  Clinton's announcement of lifting the trade embargo against 
Vietnam immediately met with welcome from U.S. enterprise 
circles. Some people from U.S. enterprise circles have held that 
Vietnam is a new hot market and said Clinton's decision will 
open up a new channel for U.S. exports and investment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

