<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Lifting Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302235994 Beijing XINHUA in English 2342 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302235994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 3 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton announced today the lifting of the 19-year-old 
trade embargo against Vietnam. 
  "I am absolutely convinced it offers the best way to resolve 
the fate of those who remain missing and about whom we are not 
sure," Clinton said at the White House. 
  Clinton said Vietnam has made "significant tangible 
progress" 
in helping resolve the issue of POWs and MIAs in the Vietnam war. 
  Clinton made the announcement after meeting with 
representatives of the families of soldiers still missing. 
  Two U.S. veterans' groups had urged Clinton not to lift the 
embargo until all American servicemen missing since the war have 
been accounted for. 
  The President vowed that he remains personally "committed to 
continuing the search for the answers and the peace of mind that 
the families of the missing deserve." 
  "I have carefully considered the questions of how best to 
sustain that cooperation in securing the fullest possible 
accounting," Clinton said. 
  "I have consulted with my national security and veterans' 
affairs advisers," he added, "it was their view that the key to 
continued progress lies in expanding our contacts with Vietnam." 
  "I have made the judgment that the best way to ensure 
cooperation from Vietnam and to continue getting the information 
Americans want on POWs and MIAs is to end the trade embargo," 
Clinton said. 
  The President also announced that he has decided to 
establish 
a liaison office in Vietnam to "provide services for Americans 
there and help us to pursue a human rights dialogue with the 
Vietnamese Government." 
  But Clinton made clear that "these actions do not constitute 
a normalization of our relationships." 
  "Before that happens," the president stressed, "we must have 
more progress, more cooperation, and more answers." 

</TEXT>

