<H3> <TI>   Trade, Refugee Officials Praise Lifting of SRV Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0402065294 Hong Kong RTHK Radio Four in English 0500 GMT 4 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0402065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong RTHK Radio Four </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at One" program] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] The Trade Development Council 
[TDC] Executive Director Francis Lo says business in the region 
will benefit from the lifting of the embargo, and the profile of 
Hong Kong will be raised. 
  [Begin Francis Lo recording] I think that, with the 
international business community now focusing more and more on 
Asia, I think the normalization of trade relationship between 
United States and Vietnam will give this focus even further 
emphasis, and I think that would certainly be very good for Asia 
as a whole and very good for Hong Kong in particular, because 
Hong Kong is the operational base for a lot of international 
companies. It is the ideal marketing headquarters for these 
companies, and it is also a sourcing [as heard] center for any 
company wishing to buy products from this part of the world. I 
think it will actually reinforce Hong Kong's position as Asia's 
trade capital. [end recording] [passage omitted] 
  The refugee coordinator, Brian Bresnahan, said the move by 
President Clinton would help Hong Kong solve the problem of 
Vietnamese boat people more quickly. 
  [Begin recording] [Bresnahan] I think that the lifting of 
the American trade embargo on Vietnam is good news for this 
particular problem. It will dash hopes amongst those screened 
out in our camps--and that is most of the population--that they 
might end up one day in America, they will then see more clearly 
that their only future is in Vietnam, and it will encourage them 
to go home. Certainly it is good news; it certainly enhances 
our chances of meeting a late 95-early 96 target of emptying our 
camps in Hong Kong. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Do you also think that it will have 
the effect of encouraging people who are now in Vietnam and 
might be considering coming to Hong Kong to stay there? 
  [Bresnahan] Absolutely, because of course, I mean, we have 
already said that the root of the boat people problem has always 
been in Vietnam and of course, many of the people who came here 
came because Vietnam was so poor. The lifting of the embargo 
will enhance economic activity in Vietnam and thus encourage 
people to stay where they are. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

