<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Official Views New Airport Financing Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0402024494 Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO in Chinese 3 Feb 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> HK0402024494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report: "Zhang Junsheng Says the Fourth New Airport </F>
Financial Arrangements Are Not a Lunar New Year Gift From the 
British Hong Kong Government"] 
  [Text] Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of the XINHUA News 
Agency Hong Kong Branch, pointed out yesterday that the latest 
airport financial arrangements are not a Lunar New Year gift 
from British Hong Kong to Hong Kong people and China because 
Britain ought to build the airport according to the Memorandum 
of Understanding [MOU] on the airport. As the agency has not 
received the package in question, Zhang Junsheng stated that he 
would decide on public comment only after he has learned the 
details of the package. 
  When asked by a reporter about his view on the airport 
financial arrangement package after attending the closing 
ceremony of A China Cultural Journey, Zhang said: The airport 
MOU was signed by the leaders of the two governments in 
September 1991. It has been two years since the document was 
signed. The British Hong Kong authorities ought to have 
conducted affairs conscientiously according to the provisions of 
the MOU and should not have stalled. Therefore, he believes that 
Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten's analogy of a Lunar New Year 
gift to Hong Kong people and China is wrong. 
  Zhang criticized Britain for coming up with so many 
packages, 
but they either did not comply with the MOU or threaten to leave 
the special administrative region [SAR] government with a huge 
burden. Naturally, China could not agree. Thus it is not a gift 
from British Hong Kong to the public; it is something that 
everybody is entitled to. 
  Zhang continued: The airport is in Hong Kong and the money 
spent is all Hong Kong taxpayers' money. It should benefit Hong 
Kong people and should not increase their burdens, and in 
particular, it should not leave a burden on the future SAR 
government. There are only three years and five months left 
before Hong Kong reverts to China. Therefore, it should not 
leave a burden on Hong Kong; the SAR is going to be in Hong Kong 
for a long, long time. 

</TEXT>

