<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign-Funded Firms To Boost Foreign Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0402065794 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 4 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0402065794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Liang Chao: "Foreign Enterprises Set To Boom This Year"] </F>
  [Text] Foreign-funded enterprises, which reached a total 
of more than 140,000 last year, will continue to play a key role 
in boosting China's foreign trade this year, according to 
official sources. 
  But the growth of their imports led to a record trade 
deficit 
of $12.18 billion last year. 
  And this trend is expected to continue this year with a 
sharp 
increase in joint-venture imports, Chinese customs officials 
predicted yesterday. 
  The foreign-funded firms' trade volume is predicted to hit a 
record high of $94 billion this year, accounting for about 40 
per cent of the country's total expected trade. This compares 
with 34 per cent last year. 
  Equipment imported by the overseas ventures totalled a 
record 
$16.6 billion in 1993 and became the most important factor in 
China's trade deficit. 
  And equipment imports are likely to double this year to 
somewhere in excess of $34 billion, the Beijing-based General 
Administration of Customs (GAC) said yesterday. 
  The officials made it clear that the rate of overseas 
investment will increase now that China has unified its foreign 
exchange rate this year. 
  Investment will be cushioned against financial risk of the 
old market where hard currrency was sold at the low official 
rate sometimes and bought on the foreign exchange at the high 
swap market rate. 
  Meanwhile, overseas firms' exports are expected to grow more 
than 35 per cent this year to reach a total value of over $34 
billion. 
  But the increase of the overseas ventures' imports and 
exports will impose a major strain on China's efforts to improve 
its balance of payments this year. 
  And China's foreign exchange market, which is still weak 
because supply and demand are the same, is likely to be affected 
. 
  And the net import of funds over the last few years will 
swing round to a net export this year. The sharp increase in 
accumulated foreign business investment will mean an increase in 
the amount of hard currencies used by them to repay capital with 
interest. 
  Efforts to balance supply and demand in the foreign exchange 
market will be further impaired by the increasingly large 
remittances which will be sent abroad by overseas ventures this 
year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26231 </DOCNO>
