<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   TV Lecture Series To Publicize Economic Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402055194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0257 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0402055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By RENMIN RIBAO reporter Wang Xuexiao (3769 1331 1321) and </F>
XINHUA reporter Zhang Shuying (1728 3219 5391)] 
  [Text] Tianjin, 4 Feb (XINHUA) -- A lecture series aimed 
at publicizing reform among the masses and enlisting their 
participation in the ongoing profound economic structural reform 
has kicked off in Tianjin; it will be broadcast throughout the 
nation starting from 6 February. 
  Sponsored by the Propaganda Department of the CPC Central 
Committee and the General Office of the State Council, the 
lectures are designed to enable leading comrades and people 
across the country to have a good grasp of the guidelines of the 
"Decision of the CPC Central Committee on Some Issues Concerning 
the Establishment of a Socialist Market Economic Structure" and 
to familiarize themselves and understand the basic contents of 
the profound reforms in the systems of finance and taxation, 
banking, investment, foreign trade, enterprises, and so forth. 
  The nine lectures in the televised series are given by 
leading officials of relevant central government departments. 
The speakers and contents of their lectures are as follow: 
  Vice Minister of the State Planning Commission Zeng Peiyan 
on 
the great significance and main contents of the "decision;" 
  Vice Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng on reform of the 
financial system; 
  Deputy Director Yang Chongchun of the State Administration 
of 
Taxation on reform of the system of taxation; 
  Vice Governor Zhou Zhengqing of the People's Bank of China 
on 
reform of the banking system; 
  Zhu Xiaohua, vice governor of the People's Bank of China and 
director of the State Foreign Exchange Administration, on reform 
of the foreign exchange system; 
  Vice Minister of the State Planning Commission Guo Shuyan on 
reform of the investment structure; 
  Vice Minister of the State Planning Commission Luo Zhiling 
on 
price-forming mechanisms; 
  Vice Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi 
Guangsheng on reform of the foreign trade system; and 
  Vice Minister of State Economics and Trade Commission Chen 
Qingtai on modern enterprise systems. The nine lectures cover 
the major issues involved in the ongoing efforts to establish a 
socialist market economic system. Gao Dezhan, secretary of the 
Tianjin Municipal CPC Committee, presided over the lectures. 
Tianjin Mayor Zhang Lichang and leading officials at all levels, 
over 1,000 in all, attended the lectures. 
  Also present at the lectures were leading comrades of the 
relevant departments and commissions including Xu Weicheng, 
executive deputy director of the Propaganda Department of the 
CPC Central Committee; Li Shizhong, deputy secretary general of 
the State Council; Yang Changji, vice Minister of the State 
Economics and Trade Commission; Lu Baifu, deputy director of 
the Development Research Center [jing jin fa zhan zhong xin 4842 
3444 4099 1455 0022 1800] of the State Council. Xu Weicheng 
noted: China is now in a crucial period of establishing a 
socialist market economic system. It is a task of top priority 
to disseminate, among the vast ranks of cadres, new ideas, new 
knowledge, and new approaches in regard to developing socialist 
market economy. In conscientiously studying Comrade Deng 
Xiaoping's theory on building socialism with Chinese 
characteristics, we must organize people to study the basic 
ideas and theory of socialist market economy. This televised 
lecture series represents a concrete step in providing education 
and training to leading cadres at all levels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26235 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi024_n_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation To Promote Nonstate-Owned Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302160294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1532 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Jing Shuping, 
chairman of the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce, 
pledged today to bring into full play the role of 
non-governmental chambers of commerce in promoting the growth of 
the non-state-owned economic sector. 
  The Federation, also known as the National Non-Governmental 
Chamber of Commerce, now has 670,000 members throughout the 
country and 2,299 local organizations at and above the county 
level. 
  Speaking at a spring festival reception attended by Chinese 
and foreign guests, Jing Shuping said that his federation will 
try to promote economic, technological and trade cooperation 
between China and other countries. 
  The Federation will also help expand cooperation between 
mainland dealers and manufacturers and their colleagues in 
Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macao and in foreign countries, he added. 
  "In particular, we will help businesses within the 
non-state-owned sector make great progress in economic, 
technological and trade cooperation with their overseas 
counterparts," he told the reception. 
  To date, the Federation has established cooperative ties 
with 
nearly 100 chambers of commerce overseas, he said. 
  Jing extended thanks to foreign embassies in Beijing and 
commercial offices for their support of the Federation. 

</TEXT>

