<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Reportedly Wants To Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302133194 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0302133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] As ROC [Republic of China] Premier Lien Chan 
returned to Taiwan on Tuesday from his second overseas trip in a 
month, President Li Teng-hui's private (?visit) to Indonesia was 
still in limbo and Foreign Minister Frederick Chien was reported 
of planning to resign. Chien, currently in Boston, was reported 
as wanting to resign due to frustration of the impasse to 
broaden diplomatic relations and internal opposition to 
diplomatic policies from the Legislature, local papers reported. 
Presidential aide said Li has made no concrete plans to go 
abroad, denying a local newspaper report that the president will 
leave for Bali on February 9 and will meet with Indonesian 
President Suharto. 
  Esther Kuo, a presidential spokeswoman, said that once the 
president's overseas travel plan matures, the office will 
announce that at the proper time. Kuo urged the media not to 
play up Li's possible trip, saying the (?extension) of the 
itinerary will create unnecessary trouble. She said that the 
pressure from Peking was the apparent obstacle, saying Li's 
travel plan over the past two years were aborted due to the 
similar obstacle. 

</TEXT>

