<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEF, ARATS Officials Meet in Beijing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Continuing Talks Discussed </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302153994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1517 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- The Association of 
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) of the Chinese 
Mainland this morning suggested continuing discussions with the 
Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) on the issue of 
Taiwan investment on the mainland. 
  ARATS also expressed hope that there will be mutual visits 
between industrial and commercial circles and scientific and 
technological personnel on the two sides across the Taiwan 
Straits. 
  Zhao Zhengyu and Li Yafei, deputy secretary-general of 
ARATS, 
held a group meeting with Shih Chi-ping, deputy 
secretary-general of SEF, this morning, a preparation for a 
meeting between major officials of the two organizations 
tomorrow. 
  ARATS suggested continuing to discuss the issue of Taiwan 
businessmen's rights and interests and other related issues in 
the second quarter of this year, Li Yafei said at a press 
conference after the meeting. 
  At the same time, the issue of unifying the scientific and 
technological terms and standardizing scales of products to 
improve exchanges regarding computers and other industries will 
be discussed, Li said. 
  The venue will be Beijing or Taipei. 
  ARATS also suggested that the two bodies start to discuss 
issues of strengthening co-development of and exchanges in 
energy and other resources in 1994. 
  Both sides agreed that economic and scientific and 
technological exchanges should be advanced on the principle of 
an agreement reached between ARATS President Wang Daohan and SEF 
chairman Ku Chen-fu last year. 
  Shih Chi-ping expressed full understanding of ARATS's 
suggestions, saying that SEF would respond to them soon. 
  Two other deputy secretaries-general of ARATS and SEF also 
held a group meeting on issues concerning routine affairs this 
morning. 
  Both sides reckoned that they should consolidate the 
achievements that have been made. 

</TEXT>

