<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubei To Improve Investment Environment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402061794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0534 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0402061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, February 4 (XINHUA) -- Central China's Hubei 
Province invested over five billion yuan to cover the 
construction of basic facilities involving transport, posts and 
telecommunications, and the power industry last year. 
  Local officials said the investment made up 30 percent of 
the 
province's entire investment in fixed assets. 
  Hubei overfulfilled its targets of opening and installing 
190,000 new telephone lines, increasing generating capacity by 
1.46 million kw, and completing 2,600 km of new high-grade 
highways in the past year. 
  In addition, the province has also opened 50 domestic and 
overseas air routes. 
  The Tianhe international airport in this provincial capital 
has finished its extension work and will go back into operation 
next month. Two other airports capable of handling Boeing jets 
in Enshi, the prefectural seat of Enshi, and in Shashi, a new 
light industrial city, have also been completed and have gone 
into use. 
  The improved investment environment has greatly enhanced 
Hubei's appeal to overseas investors. Foreign investment keeps 
pouring into the province's major cities of Wuhan, Huangshi and 
Yichang. 
  Meanwhile, statistics show that Hubei approved the 
establishment of 2,188 new foreign-funded enterprises last year, 
943 more than in the previous year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

