<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubei Reports Foreign Investment Boom </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402033794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0322 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0402033794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, February 4 (XINHUA) -- More and more foreign 
investors are putting their money into the central China 
province of Hubei. 
  In 1993 the province approved the establishment of 2,188 new 
foreign-funded enterprises, involving an agreed use of 1.9 
billion U.S. dollars in foreign funds. The figures represent 
75.74 percent and 98.53 percent increases, respectively, 
compared with 1992. 
  According to local officials, Hubei has so far approved the 
establishment of 3,433 foreign-funded enterprises, which are 
expected to bring in a total of 3.2 billion U.S. dollars in 
foreign investment. 
  Local officials attributed the foreign investment boom in 
the 
province to the implementation of the national strategy for 
opening and speeding up the development of areas along the Chang 
Jiang river, overseas investment promotion events, the 
increasingly improved investment environment and effective 
measures made to simplify approval procedures. 
  Operational foreign-funded enterprises in the province are 
reporting good production and operation achievements, and a 
rapid growth of exports of their products. 
  The 1,000 foreign-funded enterprises in operation realized 
3.23 billion yuan from sales of their products last year, 
generating 197 million yuan in local revenue. 
  These enterprises have earned 188 million U.S. dollars from 
exports in the past year, accounting for 11.2 percent of the 
province's total export earnings, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

