<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tianjin Uses Foreign Funds for Technical Upgrading </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402063094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0552 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0402063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, February 4 (XINHUA) -- North China's 
industrial city of Tianjin plans to complete the technical 
upgrading of all its state-owned industrial enterprises in eight 
years by using overseas funds. 
  Last year the city's industrial enterprises signed 197 
contracts on setting up foreign-funded firms, with a total 
investment of 596 million U.S. dollars -- 83 percent and 88 
percent increases, respectively, over the previous year. Of the 
total investment, 200 million U.S. dollars came from foreign 
investors. 
  Some 66 foreign-funded firms went into operation last year. 
  By the end of 1993 Tianjin had registered a total of 674 
foreign-funded industrial firms with a total investment of 2.36 
billion U.S. dollars. 
  Their registered capital came to 1.74 billion U.S. dollars, 
of which some 873 million U.S. dollars came from foreign 
investors. 
  The city now has 187 foreign-funded firms in operation. They 
have 43,000 employees. 
  In 1993 Tianjin's foreign-funded enterprises recorded an 
industrial production value of 7.33 billion yuan (about 900 
million U.S. dollars) and profits of 750 million yuan, and 
handed over taxes of one billion yuan. 
  By the end of last year 227 enterprises had started 
technical 
upgrading programs by using a total of 590 million U.S. dollars 
in overseas funds. 
  The technical upgrading programs have helped enterprises 
improve product quality, technology and management. 
  At the same time, the city has paid special attention to 
strengthening cooperation with international big-name 
corporations. 
  In the past two years Tianjin has encouraged a number of its 
major electronics, motorcycle, refrigerator, washing machine and 
detergent firms to seek cooperation with big foreign companies, 
such as Hankel of Germany, Samsung of the Republic of Korea, 
Honda of Japan and ZEC of Italy. 
  So far, the city has set up joint ventures with more than 
100 
such companies, 18 of which have an annual production value of 
over 100 million yuan each and annual profits exceeding 10 
million yuan each. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26272 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi024_r_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tianjin Signs Joint Venture With Japapese Firm </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402114394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1118 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0402114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, February 4 (XINHUA) -- Takeda Chemical 
Industries Ltd., Japan's biggest pharmaceutical manufacturer, 
signed a contract here recently setting up a joint venture with 
the Tianjin Lisheng Pharmaceuticals Factory. 
  It is understood that with a total investment of more than 
26 
million U.S. dollars, the Tianjin Takeda Pharmaceuticals Co. Ltd 
will mainly produce such medicines as calan, adegot, AQ-128, 
enanpone and pakepron tablets, which are much needed both in the 
domestic and international markets. 
  An estimated annual sales volume worth some two billion 
Japanese yen is expected to be reached by the joint venture in 
1996. 
  Officials of the Japanese company said China is a country 
with bright prospects due to its stable political and economic 
environment, and they believed their products will enjoy good 
sales in the Chinese market, which has great potential. 
  Takeda Chemical Industries Ltd. has established some 11 
companies all over the world. It reports an annual total sales 
volume of more than 560 billion Japanese yen. 
  Its co-operative partner, the Tianjin Lisheng 
Pharmaceuticals 
Factory, which is capable of producing some five billion 
medicinal tablets per year, is one of the key pharmaceuticals 
factories in China. 
  To date, some 547 Japan-invested firms have been established 
in Tianjin, involving a total investment of some 580 million 
U.S. dollars, covering the fields of agriculture, manufacturing, 
service sector, and trade as well as real estate, according to 
official statistics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

