<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Lanqing Says Customs Must Serve Economic Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302132794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1309 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Vice-Premier Li 
Lanqing said today that customs offices must meet the needs of a 
socialist market economy and help maintain "sustained, rapid and 
healthy" growth of China's economy. 
  Addressing a national conference on customs work which 
closed 
here today, Li said that the customs restructuring must be 
carried out simultaneously with the overall reform of China's 
economic structure. 
  It is necessary to institute a modern customs system with 
Chinese characteristics that will meet the needs of a socialist 
market economic structure and opening up, and will be compatible 
with internationally accepted practices, the leader told 
directors of customs offices from all over the country. 
  To this end, "We must introduce an inspection system, reform 
the declaration system and the customs managerial system..., 
while combining our professional restructuring with the use of 
modern technical means in an effort to establish modern, 
efficient customs offices," he said. 
  Li Lanqing urged the directors of customs offices to tighten 
supervision of import and export goods and crack down on all 
kinds of duty evasion and fraud so as to maintain a normal 
economic order. 
  "We have scored initial successes in the current 
anti-smuggling campaign, but by no means can we relax our 
efforts," he said. 
  The leader pledged to investigate and handle major smuggling 
cases promptly, noting that it is imperative to combine the 
anti-smuggling campaign with the anti-corruption campaign in 
order to ensure the healthy development of the country's 
economic construction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

