<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wu Yi Discusses Foreign Trade, Competition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302085794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0746 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 3 (XINHUA) -- Wu Yi, China's 
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, said here 
today that the country's foreign trade companies should be more 
aware of competition, so as to push forward the development of 
China's foreign trade. 
  She was speaking at a meeting of the China National 
Technical 
Import and Export Corporation. 
  She noted that China's foreign trade companies face 
increasingly severe competition with the establishment of the 
market system and China's foreign trade reforms. 
  China already has over 7,000 enterprises enjoying foreign 
trade rights, including nearly 2,000 industrial enterprises, 
over 280 barter trade corporations, and over 120 scientific 
institutions. 
  She said that this year's foreign trade target is set to 
reach 200 billion U.S. dollars, which will be a painstaking 
task. But, she noted, reforms of China's foreign exchange and 
foreign trade systems will provide new opportunities. 
  She hoped that all foreign trade companies will strive for a 
new breakthrough by keeping their eyes both on the domestic and 
overseas market, paying due attention to quality control and 
diversifying foreign trade markets. 
  She said that China will expand its technical imports and 
exports this year, with the focus on technical imports for key 
national and long-term projects such as power stations and 
telephone systems. 
  At the same time, China will enhance its export of 
equipment, 
high-tech products and high value-added products of machinery 
and electronics. 
  She also said that foreign trade companies should try to 
strengthen their overseas business management, which is a key 
point for this year's foreign trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

