<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEF, ARATS Officials Meet in Beijing </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Postive' Results Seen </H4>
<F P=102> OW0402035794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1532 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0402035794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters Fan Liqing (5400 7787 7230) and Fang Jin (2455 </F>
3866)] 
  [Text] Beijing, 3 Feb (XINHUA) -- Wang Zhaoguo, vice 
chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC] and director of the 
Taiwan Affairs Office under the CPC Central Committee, met with 
Jiao Renhe [Chiao Jen-ho], vice chairman and secretary general 
of the Straits Exchange Foundation [SEF], and his party at the 
Great Hall of the People today. 
  Wang Zhaoguo welcomed the SEF officials, who have come to 
Beijing for talks with officials of the Association for 
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits [ARATS]. He commented 
positively on the meetings between SEF and ARATS, and applauded 
SEF for keeping a channel open for contact and discussions with 
ARATS. Wang Zhaoguo said: Since its inception, ARATS has had 
many contacts and discussions with SEF, and helped advance 
contacts and discussions on routine affairs across the strait. 
Wang Daohan and Gu Zhenfu [Ku Chen-fu] had a successful meeting 
in Singapore last April, which General Secretary Jiang Zemin 
termed a successful and fruitful meeting that marked an 
important, historic step in the development of relations across 
the strait. After the Wang-Ku talks, the two organizations had 
several working discussions. This visit by Vice Chairman Jiao 
to Beijing for high-level talks is of great significance. He 
said: Regular contacts and discussions will help the two sides 
enhance mutual understanding and reach a consensus. 
  Jiao Renhe said: The SEF and ARATS have already had many 
discussions. This is my first visit to Beijing; in the past 
three days I have had two meetings with Tang Shubei and Zou 
Zhekai. The two sides have made considerable progress toward 
reaching a consensus; one thing still lacking is "convergence" 
and more efforts are needed. Jiao Renhe also said: Promoting 
cross-strait exchanges involves a host of miscellaneous 
problems. A key point is to build "mutual confidence." It is 
hoped that things will develop in ways conducive to cross-strait 
exchange and cooperation. 
  Wang Zhaoguo said: The current visit by Jiao has helped 
advance the development of cross-strait relations. After 
discussions, the two organizations have reached an understanding 
on the following four points: First, high-level officials of 
the two organizations reaffirmed the understanding on 
repatriation, in principle, of all hijackers; second, the two 
organization agreed that they should follow the principle of 
stressing the nongovernmental and routine nature of their 
discussions, eschew politically sensitive issues, and refrain 
from imposing their political demands on each other; third, it 
is essential and important to keep open a clear channel of 
contact and discussions between the two organizations; fourth, 
both sides wish to see that a second Wang-Gu meeting be held at 
an early date. 
  After the meeting, Tang Shubei briefed reporters on the 
meeting. He said: The meeting proceeded in a sincere, cordial, 
and harmonious [cheng zhi qin qie rong qia 6134 2304 6024 0434 
5816 3174] atmosphere. Wang Zhaoguo also briefed the guests the 
on progress the mainland has made in implementing the policy of 
reform and opening up over the past 15 years, and its ongoing 
efforts to develop a socialist market economy. Jiao Renhe 
briefed the hosts on the political situation in Taiwan. 
  After the meeting, Wang Zhaoguo entertained Jiao Renhe and 
SEF Deputy Secretaries General Shi Qiping [Shi Chi-ping] and Xu 
Huiyou [Hsu Hui-yu]. 
  Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of the ARATS, and Zou 
Zhekai, vice-president and secretary general of ARATS, were also 
in attendance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

